  "text": "Adding noise to inputs has been shown to provide regularization effect that theoretically is equivalent to Tikhonov regularization (Bishop 1995) . In order to understand the effect on input noise to generalisation, a simple architecture of 500 hidden layers is considered for a binary classification problem and differentiating two types of circles. Two types of noise are considered, namely, additive gaussian noise and the multiplicative gaussian noise which are commonly used for enhancing the fault tolerance of neural networks by improving the generalisation (Ho, Leung, and Sum 2010) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] In case of additive noise, on adding a small noise of standard deviation of 0.01, the generalisation performance on the binary classification problem improves. However, on increasing the values of the standard deviation, the model starts to overfit the noisy training data and the performance starts to decline. A similar phenomenon is observed on training models in the presence of worst case adversarial noise as shown in the subsequent sections.",
